# n8n best practices (blocking)

Full detail: [docs/best-practices.md](../../docs/best-practices.md).

## Naming

- Workflow and node names: **short, plain English** — readable as a story.
- Bad: `If`, `Set`, `HTTP Request`. Good: `Does user have email?`, `Fetch user profile from directory`.
- Workflow `name` is descriptive English; repo file stays `workflows/<kebab-slug>.json`.

## Error handling (every workflow)

**Preferred:** `settings.errorWorkflow` → dedicated global error-handling workflow (document name/id in ARCHITECTURE).

**Exceptional:** local Error Trigger only with justification in ARCHITECTURE. Do not ship workflows with neither.

## Reusable sub-workflows

Use to **decompose** complexity or **share** logic (e.g. email → user profile with Slack/Jira ids).

Reusable workflows require: **strict inputs/outputs**, **limited scope**, documented in specs. Treat as high-impact: limited write access in n8n; everyone can view.

Orchestrators call reusables via **Execute Workflow**; document parent/child links in ARCHITECTURE.

## Skills must enforce

- **n8n-plan** — workflow kind, error workflow, sub-workflow I/O, story node names in ARCHITECTURE.
- **n8n-build** — implement error workflow setting or justified local trigger; name nodes per story rule.
- **n8n-verify** — `[REJECT]` on generic names, missing error handling, or undocumented sub-workflow contracts.
